The paper deals with analyzing intermediate representations in convolutional neural networks, which is a common topic in the machine learning community. The use of modified RV similarity analysis is a technique commonly used in the field of machine learning, particularly in the analysis of neural networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper specifically focuses on convolutional neural networks, which suggests that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is also a likely sub-category. The use of different training techniques and their effect on the representations suggests that cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper also discusses the interpretability of the similarity matrices, which suggests that cs.CL (Computation and Language) is a possible sub-category.
